var tafsirData_37 = {
  1: {
    "By those ˹angels˺ lined up in ranks": "Allah begins this Surah by swearing an oath by the angels who stand in perfect rows before Him in worship and obedience. This imagery reflects the discipline, order, and humility of the angels as they worship Allah. Just as soldiers stand in formation before their commander, the angels stand before their Lord in absolute submission. This oath draws attention to the unseen world and reminds us that there are magnificent creatures constantly glorifying Allah. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'Do you not line up as the angels line up before their Lord?' The companions asked, 'How do the angels line up?' He replied, 'They complete the first row and stand close together in the row.' (Sahih Muslim)"
  },
  2: {
    "and those who diligently drive ˹the clouds˺": "This refers to the angels who are tasked with driving and directing the clouds by Allah's command, bringing rain to various parts of the earth. Some scholars also interpret this as angels who drive away evil or drive creatures as Allah commands. The point is that angels are active servants of Allah, carrying out His will in the universe. Nothing in creation moves without Allah's permission, and the angels are His obedient workers managing the affairs of the world as He decrees."
  },
  3: {
    "and those who recite the Reminder!": "This refers to the angels who recite the words of Allah, including the Angel Jibreel (Gabriel) who brought down the Quran to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ. The 'Reminder' is the Quran and other divine revelations. This shows that the Quran has a heavenly origin—it was not invented by any human but was delivered by the most noble of angels. When you read the Quran, you are reading the same words that angels recite in the heavens."
  },
  4: {
    "Surely your God is One!": "This is the conclusion of the oath—the main point Allah is emphasizing. After swearing by these magnificent angels, Allah declares that He alone is the true God. There is no deity worthy of worship except Him. This is the core message of Islam: Tawheed (the Oneness of God). The Arabs of Makkah worshipped many idols, but Allah affirms that all those objects of worship are false. Only He, the Creator of the angels and everything else, deserves worship. This verse shatters polytheism and calls humanity to pure monotheism."
  },
  5: {
    "˹He is˺ the Lord of the heavens and the earth and everything in between": "Allah is the Creator, Owner, and Sustainer of the heavens, the earth, and every single thing that exists between them—every planet, star, creature, plant, and atom. Nothing exists outside His dominion. He provides for all, maintains all, and controls all affairs.",
    "and the Lord of all points of sunrise": "Allah is the Lord of every place from which the sun rises. Throughout the year, the sun rises from slightly different points on the horizon, and Allah controls each one. This phrase emphasizes His absolute authority over time and space. Every new day begins by His permission, and every sunrise is a sign of His power and consistency."
  },
  6: {
    "Indeed, We have adorned the lowest heaven with the stars for decoration": "Allah beautified the sky that we can see—the nearest heaven—with stars. When you look up at night and see the stars scattered across the sky like jewels, you are witnessing Allah's artistry. The stars serve as decoration, making the night sky one of the most beautiful sights in creation. This is a gift from Allah for us to appreciate and reflect upon. The vastness and beauty of the night sky should lead us to recognize the greatness of the One who created it."
  },
  7: {
    "and ˹for˺ protection from every rebellious devil": "Besides being beautiful, the stars (or shooting stars/meteors) also serve as a defense system against rebellious devils (Shayateen) who try to ascend to the heavens. These devils are disobedient jinn who rebel against Allah's order. They attempt to eavesdrop on the conversations of the angels in the heavens to steal information about the unseen. But Allah has placed a barrier and a weapon against them."
  },
  8: {
    "They cannot listen to the highest assembly ˹of angels˺": "These rebellious devils are prevented from hearing the conversations of the angels in the upper heavens. The angels discuss matters of decree and destiny as commanded by Allah, and the devils desperately try to listen so they can pass false information to fortune-tellers and soothsayers on earth.",
    "for they are pelted from every side": "Whenever these devils try to approach the heavens, they are attacked from all directions with flaming projectiles (shooting stars). There is no escape route for them. Allah's defense is perfect and comprehensive."
  },
  9: {
    "˹fiercely˺ driven away": "They are expelled and repelled with force and humiliation. They cannot achieve their goal of stealing heavenly information.",
    "And they will suffer an everlasting torment": "Beyond being driven away in this world, these rebellious devils will face a permanent, continuous punishment in the Hereafter. Their rebellion against Allah will not go unpunished. This is a warning that disobedience to Allah has severe consequences."
  },
  10: {
    "But whoever manages to stealthily eavesdrop": "Occasionally, a devil might snatch a fragment of information from the heavens before being detected. This is a quick, secretive grab of some news.",
    "is ˹instantly˺ pursued by a piercing flare": "But even if a devil manages to catch something, it is immediately chased by a bright, burning flame—a shooting star—that pierces through and destroys it. The Prophet ﷺ explained that sometimes a devil passes the stolen information to a fortune-teller before being struck, and the fortune-teller mixes it with a hundred lies. This is why fortune-telling is forbidden in Islam—it relies on deception and stolen, corrupted information. (Sahih Bukhari)"
  },
  11: {
    "So ask them ˹O Prophet˺, which is harder to create: them or other marvels of Our creation?": "Allah instructs Prophet Muhammad ﷺ to pose a logical question to those who deny resurrection: Is recreating humans more difficult than creating the heavens, the earth, the angels, and all the magnificent things Allah has already made? Obviously not. The One who created the entire universe with such precision can easily bring back humans to life. This is a powerful argument against those who doubt resurrection.",
    "Indeed, We created them from a sticky clay": "Allah reminds us of our humble origin. Humans were created from clay—sticky, moldable earth. If Allah could create complex human beings from simple clay in the first place, how can anyone doubt His ability to recreate them after death? Our origin should humble us and make us recognize Allah's limitless power."
  },
  12: {
    "In fact, you are astonished ˹by their denial˺, while they ridicule ˹you˺": "The Prophet ﷺ was amazed at how the disbelievers could deny such clear truths. Despite all the signs around them, they rejected the message. And instead of reflecting seriously, they mocked the Prophet ﷺ and the revelation. This verse shows the sad irony: the one with the truth is astonished by their blindness, while the blind ones laugh at the truth. This pattern repeats throughout history—truth-bearers are often mocked by those who refuse to see."
  },
  13: {
    "When they are reminded, they are never mindful": "When these deniers hear reminders about Allah, death, resurrection, and accountability, they do not pay attention or take heed. They let the words pass without reflection. Their hearts have become hard, and they are not interested in guidance. This is a warning for all of us: when we hear the Quran or good advice, we should reflect and let it change us, not ignore it like the heedless ones."
  },
  14: {
    "And whenever they see a sign, they make fun of it": "When a clear sign or miracle comes to them—whether in nature or through revelation—instead of believing, they mock it. They treat sacred matters as jokes. This attitude of mockery is a sign of arrogance and a hardened heart. Those who ridicule Allah's signs are only harming themselves."
  },
  15: {
    "saying, \"This is nothing but pure magic.\"": "The disbelievers dismissed the Quran and the Prophet's miracles as mere magic or sorcery. They could not deny the extraordinary nature of what they witnessed, but instead of accepting the truth, they made excuses. Calling truth 'magic' was their way of avoiding accountability. This excuse has been used by deniers throughout history whenever they encounter something they cannot explain away."
  },
  16: {
    "When we are dead and reduced to dust and bones, will we really be resurrected?": "The disbelievers expressed disbelief at the concept of bodily resurrection. They asked mockingly: After we die and our bodies decompose into dust and bones, will we actually be brought back to life? To their limited understanding, this seemed impossible. But they failed to consider Allah's unlimited power—the same power that created them from nothing in the first place."
  },
  17: {
    "And our forefathers as well?": "They added sarcastically: Even our ancient ancestors who died long ago—will they be resurrected too? Their bones have turned to dust centuries ago. This question was meant to ridicule the idea further. But Allah, who has perfect knowledge of every atom that ever existed, will reassemble every person exactly as they were."
  },
  18: {
    "Say, \"Yes! And you will be fully humbled.\"": "Allah commands the Prophet ﷺ to respond with a firm 'Yes!' Resurrection will definitely happen. And when it does, these mockers will be humiliated and brought low. The arrogance they displayed in this world will be replaced with complete humiliation. Those who laughed at the truth will face a reality they cannot escape or deny. This is a powerful warning: mockery of Allah's message has consequences."
  },
  19: {
    "It will only take one Blast, then at once they will see ˹it all˺": "The resurrection will not be a slow, gradual process. It will happen instantly with a single blast—the blowing of the trumpet by the angel Israfil. In that moment, every human who ever lived will be raised and will see the reality of the Day of Judgment before their eyes. The same people who mocked will now witness the truth they denied. There will be no time to prepare or escape."
  },
  20: {
    "They will cry, \"Oh, woe to us! This is the Day of Judgment!\"": "When the deniers see the reality of that Day, they will cry out in regret and despair: 'Woe to us! This is the Day of Judgment!' The same Day they mocked and denied is now undeniably in front of them. Their cries of 'woe' express deep anguish and the realization that it is too late to change anything. This is the moment when denial turns to horrified acknowledgment."
  },
  21: {
    "˹They will be told,˺ \"This is the Day of ˹Final˺ Decision which you used to deny.\"": "A voice will announce to them that this is the Day of Decision—the Day when truth is separated from falsehood, believers from disbelievers, and the righteous from the wicked. This is the very Day they called a lie. Now they must face its reality. There is no escaping the decision that will be made about their eternal fate."
  },
  22: {
    "˹Allah will say to the angels,˺ \"Gather ˹all˺ the wrongdoers along with their peers, and whatever they used to worship": "Allah will command the angels to gather all the wrongdoers—those who committed injustice, disbelieved, and transgressed. They will be gathered with others like them (their companions in sin, their families who shared their disbelief, or their partners in crime). Also gathered will be the false gods they worshipped—whether idols, humans, or anything else they associated with Allah. Everyone and everything involved in their misguidance will be assembled together."
  },
  23: {
    "instead of Allah, then lead them ˹all˺ to the path of Hell": "All those who worshipped anything other than Allah will be directed to the path leading to Hell. The word 'path' here is deeply ironic—they rejected the Straight Path (Sirat al-Mustaqeem) to Paradise in this life, so now they are guided to another path: the path to Hellfire. What a terrible destination for those who refused guidance."
  },
  24: {
    "And detain them, for they must be questioned": "Before entering Hell, they will be stopped and questioned. Allah will hold them accountable for their beliefs and actions. They will be asked about their worship, their deeds, and their response to the messengers. This questioning is part of Allah's perfect justice—no one will be punished without being given a chance to answer for themselves."
  },
  25: {
    "˹Then they will be asked,˺ \"What is the matter with you that you can no longer help each other?\"": "They will be asked mockingly: Why aren't you helping each other now? In the worldly life, they supported each other in disbelief and sin. They formed alliances against the truth. But now, each person is alone, unable to help themselves or anyone else. The bonds of evil friendship dissolve completely on that Day. This is a powerful lesson: the only relationships that will benefit us in the Hereafter are those built on faith and righteousness."
  },
  26: {
    "In fact, on that Day they will be ˹fully˺ submissive": "On that Day, the arrogant will become completely submissive. Those who refused to submit to Allah in this life will have no choice but to submit on the Day of Judgment. Their pride will be shattered, and they will be utterly helpless before Allah's authority. The submission they refused to give willingly will be forced upon them."
  },
  27: {
    "They will turn on each other, throwing blame": "When the wrongdoers realize their fate, they will turn against one another. The unity they had in sin will collapse into bitter accusations. Friends will become enemies. Followers will blame their leaders, and leaders will try to shift responsibility. This scene shows the true nature of relationships not built on truth—they fall apart when it matters most."
  },
  28: {
    "The misled will say, \"It was you who deluded us away from what is right.\"": "Those who were led astray will confront those who misled them. They will accuse them: 'You came to us from a position of authority and trust (from the right—symbolizing power and influence), and you deceived us away from the truth.' They will blame their leaders, teachers, friends, or anyone who convinced them to reject the message of Allah."
  },
  29: {
    "The misleaders will reply, \"No! You disbelieved on your own.\"": "The misleaders will defend themselves by saying: We didn't force you to disbelieve—you chose disbelief yourselves. You were not believers to begin with. You had your own free will and you made your own choices. They will refuse to accept full responsibility, pointing out that each person had the ability to think and choose."
  },
  30: {
    "We had no authority over you": "The misleaders will argue that they had no real power to force anyone into disbelief. They didn't control anyone's mind or will. They merely invited, and others accepted.",
    "In fact, you yourselves were a transgressing people": "They will accuse the misled of being transgressors themselves—people who were already inclined toward sin and rebellion. They didn't need much convincing because they wanted to follow their desires anyway. This argument shows that on the Day of Judgment, no excuse will work—everyone will try to blame someone else, but each person is responsible for their own choices."
  },
  31: {
    "The decree of our Lord has come to pass against us ˹all˺: we will certainly taste ˹the punishment˺": "The misleaders will finally admit the truth: Allah's decree of punishment has been justified against all of them. Both the misleaders and the misled will taste the punishment. There is no escape now. The games of blame are meaningless—the punishment is coming regardless."
  },
  32: {
    "We caused you to deviate, for we ourselves were deviant": "In a moment of terrible honesty, the misleaders will confess: Yes, we led you astray, but only because we ourselves were astray. The blind were leading the blind into a pit. This is a warning about following people without verifying their guidance. If your teachers, friends, or leaders are themselves misguided, following them will only lead to shared destruction."
  },
  33: {
    "Surely on that Day they will ˹all˺ share in the punishment": "Allah concludes this scene by stating that both groups—the misleaders and the misled—will share in the punishment together. Neither group escapes. Following someone into sin does not reduce your punishment, and leading others into sin only increases yours. The only way to safety is to follow the truth that Allah revealed, regardless of what others around you choose to do."
  },
  34: {
    "That is certainly how We deal with the wicked": "Allah declares that the punishment described for the misleaders and the misled is His established way of dealing with criminals and wicked people. This is not random or unjust—it is Allah's consistent system. Those who persist in wickedness, reject truth, and lead others astray will face these consequences. Allah's justice is perfect and applies equally to all wrongdoers throughout history."
  },
  35: {
    "For whenever it was said to them ˹in the world˺, \"There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Allah,\" they acted arrogantly": "Allah explains the root cause of their punishment: arrogance. When the message of Tawheed (the Oneness of Allah) was presented to them—the simple and pure declaration that there is no deity worthy of worship except Allah—they responded with pride and rejection. They refused to humble themselves before Allah. Arrogance is one of the most dangerous sins because it prevents a person from accepting truth. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'No one who has an atom's weight of arrogance in his heart will enter Paradise.' (Sahih Muslim)"
  },
  36: {
    "and argued, \"Should we really abandon our gods for a mad poet?\"": "Instead of evaluating the message on its own merit, the disbelievers attacked the messenger. They called Prophet Muhammad ﷺ a 'mad poet'—someone who was crazy and just making up beautiful words. They asked mockingly if they should leave the gods their ancestors worshipped for centuries just because of what this 'poet' says. This is a common tactic of those who reject truth: attack the messenger personally rather than address the message itself. Their attachment to their false gods was based on tradition and pride, not reason or evidence."
  },
  37: {
    "In fact, he came with the truth, confirming ˹earlier˺ messengers": "Allah refutes their accusations completely. The Prophet Muhammad ﷺ was neither mad nor a mere poet—he came with the absolute truth from Allah. Furthermore, his message was not new or strange; it confirmed what all previous messengers had taught: worship Allah alone. From Adam to Noah to Abraham to Moses to Jesus, every prophet brought the same core message. Muhammad ﷺ is the final link in this blessed chain of prophets, all calling humanity to the same truth."
  },
  38: {
    "You will certainly taste the painful torment": "Allah addresses the disbelievers directly with a definite warning: they will absolutely taste painful punishment. The word 'certainly' emphasizes that this is not a possibility but a guarantee for those who persist in arrogance and rejection. The punishment will be painful and real—not something they can avoid or negotiate their way out of."
  },
  39: {
    "and will only be rewarded for what you used to do": "Allah's justice is emphasized again: people will only be recompensed according to their own deeds. No one will be punished for what they didn't do, and no one will escape punishment for what they did do. This is perfect fairness. Allah doesn't wrong anyone—people wrong themselves by choosing disbelief and sin. Every action, big or small, is recorded and will be accounted for."
  },
  40: {
    "But not the chosen servants of Allah": "After describing the fate of the wicked, Allah now turns to the believers. The 'chosen servants' or 'sincere servants' of Allah are exempted from that punishment. These are the people who worshipped Allah with sincerity, not for show or worldly gain. They purified their intentions and devoted themselves to Allah alone. Sincerity (Ikhlas) is what separates true believers from hypocrites. Allah chose them because they chose Him."
  },
  41: {
    "They will have a known provision": "These sincere servants will receive a special, guaranteed provision from Allah. The word 'known' indicates that it is certain, determined, and specifically designated for them. Unlike worldly provisions which are uncertain and fluctuate, this provision in Paradise is secure and eternal. They will never worry about losing it or it running out."
  },
  42: {
    "fruits ˹of every type˺": "Their provision includes fruits of all kinds—fruits that exist in this world and fruits that no eye has ever seen and no mind has ever imagined. These are not ordinary fruits; they are the fruits of Paradise, perfect in taste, appearance, and abundance.",
    "And they will be honoured": "Beyond physical provisions, Allah will honor them. They will be treated with dignity and respect, elevated in status, and recognized for their faith and patience. In this world, believers may face humiliation for their faith, but in the Hereafter, they will be the honored ones."
  },
  43: {
    "in the Gardens of Bliss": "All of this will take place in the Gardens of Bliss—Paradise (Jannah). These are gardens of complete happiness, pleasure, and delight. There is no sadness, pain, worry, or fear there. Everything in Paradise is designed for eternal bliss. The Prophet ﷺ said that Allah has prepared for His righteous servants what no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has imagined. (Sahih Bukhari)"
  },
  44: {
    "facing each other on thrones": "The people of Paradise will sit on elegant thrones, facing one another. This arrangement allows for friendly conversation, companionship, and enjoyment of each other's company. There is no loneliness in Paradise. The believers will be reunited with their righteous family members and friends, enjoying eternal fellowship. The image of facing thrones shows honor, relaxation, and beautiful social interaction."
  },
  45: {
    "A drink ˹of pure wine˺ will be passed around to them from a flowing stream": "Servants will circulate among the people of Paradise offering them drinks from a pure, flowing spring. This wine of Paradise is not like the impure alcohol of this world—it is pure, from a continuously flowing source that never runs dry. The service they receive reflects their honored status. They don't need to fetch anything themselves; everything is brought to them."
  },
  46: {
    "crystal-white, delicious to drink": "This drink is described as crystal-white and pure in appearance, and absolutely delicious in taste. It brings pure pleasure to those who drink it. Unlike worldly drinks that may look good but taste bad, or taste good but have harmful effects, this drink is perfect in every way—beautiful to look at and delightful to consume."
  },
  47: {
    "It will neither harm ˹them˺, nor will they be intoxicated by it": "The wine of Paradise has no negative effects whatsoever. It doesn't cause headaches, sickness, hangovers, or loss of senses. It doesn't make people drunk, foolish, or out of control. It provides all the pleasure without any of the harm. This is why alcohol is forbidden in this world—its harms outweigh its benefits—but in Paradise, Allah provides a perfect alternative with pure pleasure and no harm."
  },
  48: {
    "And with them will be maidens of modest gaze and gorgeous eyes": "The men of Paradise will have companions—beautiful maidens who are modest, lowering their gaze and devoted only to their husbands. They have large, beautiful eyes that are captivating. These companions are part of the blessings Allah has prepared for the believers. Their modesty and beauty represent perfection in character and appearance."
  },
  49: {
    "as if they were pristine pearls": "These maidens are compared to hidden, protected pearls—pure, precious, and untouched. Just as a pearl kept in its shell is preserved in perfect condition, these companions are flawless and pure. This imagery emphasizes their purity, beauty, and the great value Allah places on them as a reward for the believers."
  },
  50: {
    "Then they will turn to one another inquisitively": "The people of Paradise will engage in conversations with each other, asking questions and sharing experiences. Unlike the hostile confrontations of the people of Hell (who blamed each other), these conversations are friendly and reflective. They will reminisce about their worldly lives and how Allah saved them. This shows that Paradise is not just physical pleasure but also includes meaningful social connections."
  },
  51: {
    "One of them will say, \"I once had a companion ˹in the world˺": "One of the believers will share a story about someone he knew in the worldly life—a close companion, perhaps a friend, colleague, or associate. This companion had influenced him or tried to influence his beliefs. The believer recalls this relationship as he reflects on how far he has come and how blessed he is to be in Paradise."
  },
  52: {
    "who used to ask ˹me˺, 'Do you actually believe ˹in resurrection˺?": "The believer recalls how his worldly companion used to question and mock his faith. The companion would ask sarcastically: Do you really believe in resurrection? Do you actually think we will be brought back to life after we die? This was said in a tone of disbelief and ridicule, trying to make the believer doubt his faith."
  },
  53: {
    "When we are dead and reduced to dust and bones, will we really be brought to judgment?'\"": "The skeptical companion continued his mockery: After we die and our bodies decompose into dust and bones, do you really think we will be judged? He found the concept of resurrection and accountability absurd and impossible. This is the same argument disbelievers have used throughout history. But now, standing in Paradise, the believer knows the truth."
  },
  54: {
    "He will ˹then˺ ask, \"Would you care to see ˹his fate˺?\"": "The believer in Paradise, curious about what happened to his old companion, will ask the others around him: Would you like to see where he ended up? This is not asked out of cruelty but out of amazement and gratitude—amazement at how their paths diverged and gratitude that Allah saved him from a similar fate."
  },
  55: {
    "Then he ˹and the others˺ will look and spot him in the midst of the Hellfire": "The believer will then look down and see his former companion right in the middle of the Hellfire. The one who mocked resurrection and judgment is now experiencing exactly what he denied. This scene is a powerful reminder that the choices we make in this life have eternal consequences. The believer sees with his own eyes the fate of those who reject truth."
  },
  56: {
    "He will ˹then˺ say, \"By Allah! You nearly ruined me.\"": "The believer will address his former companion (whether directly or as a reflection): By Allah, you almost destroyed me! You almost convinced me to abandon my faith. Your doubts and mockery nearly led me astray. This shows how dangerous bad companionship can be—friends who mock faith can lead a person to eternal destruction."
  },
  57: {
    "Had it not been for the grace of my Lord, I ˹too˺ would have certainly been among those brought ˹to Hell˺": "The believer acknowledges that only Allah's grace saved him. It was not his own intelligence or strength that protected him from misguidance—it was Allah's mercy and guidance. Without Allah's favor, he would have been among those dragged to Hell. This is a lesson in humility: our salvation comes from Allah, and we should never feel arrogant about our faith. We should constantly thank Allah for guiding us and ask Him to keep us firm."
  },
  58: {
    "˹Then he will ask his fellow believers,˺ \"Can you imagine that we will never die\"": "The believer, overwhelmed with joy, will turn to his companions in Paradise and express amazement: Can you believe it? We will never die again! Death is behind us forever. In Paradise, there is no death, no ending, no fear of losing what we have. This is the eternal life that every soul yearns for."
  },
  59: {
    "except our first death, nor be punished ˹like the others˺?\"": "The only death they ever experienced was the first one in the worldly life. After that, they have been granted eternal life in Paradise with no punishment whatsoever. They see the people of Hell suffering while they themselves are safe and blessed. This realization fills them with profound gratitude and joy."
  },
  60: {
    "This is truly the ultimate triumph": "The believer declares that this—Paradise, eternal life, safety from punishment, and Allah's pleasure—is the greatest success possible. Nothing in the worldly life can compare to this triumph. All the wealth, power, and fame of the world mean nothing compared to entering Paradise. This is what every person should strive for."
  },
  61: {
    "For such ˹honour˺ all should strive": "Allah concludes this passage with a powerful call to action: For a reward like this, let everyone strive! Let the workers work and the strivers compete. If there is anything worth working hard for, it is Paradise. All our efforts, sacrifices, and struggles in this life should be directed toward earning Allah's pleasure and this ultimate reward. This verse motivates believers to prioritize the Hereafter over temporary worldly gains. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'Be in this world as if you were a stranger or a traveler.' (Sahih Bukhari) Our true home is the Hereafter."
  },
  62: {
    "Is this ˹bliss˺ a better accommodation or the tree of Zaqqûm?": "Allah poses a rhetorical question, asking which is better: the incredible bliss of Paradise just described—the fruits, drinks, companions, and eternal joy—or the tree of Zaqqum? The answer is obvious, but the question forces reflection. It makes the reader consider their choices and which destination they are working toward. The contrast is stark: Paradise with its delights versus Hell with its horrors."
  },
  63: {
    "We have surely made it a test for the wrongdoers": "Allah explains that the tree of Zaqqum is a trial and test for the wrongdoers. When the disbelievers of Makkah heard about this tree, they mocked it, saying: How can a tree grow in fire? Fire burns trees! They used this as an excuse to reject the Quran. But they failed to understand that Allah's power is unlimited—He can create whatever He wills, including a tree that thrives in Hellfire. Their mockery only increased their sin and sealed their fate."
  },
  64: {
    "Indeed, it is a tree that grows in the depths of Hell": "Allah describes where this tree is located: it grows from the very bottom of Hell, the lowest and most severe part of the punishment. Its roots are in the deepest pit of the Fire. This tree is not like any tree on earth—it is a creation of Allah specifically designed as a torment for the people of Hell."
  },
  65: {
    "bearing fruit like devils' heads": "The fruit of this cursed tree looks like the heads of devils. Even though people have not seen actual devils' heads, the image evokes extreme ugliness and terror. Just as people imagine devils to be hideous and frightening, the fruit of Zaqqum is indescribably horrific in appearance. Everything about this tree—its location, appearance, and taste—is designed to add to the torment of its consumers."
  },
  66: {
    "The evildoers will certainly ˹be left to˺ eat from it, filling up their bellies with it": "Despite its horrifying appearance and taste, the people of Hell will be forced to eat from this tree. They will be so hungry that they will fill their stomachs with it. There is no other food for them. The Prophet ﷺ described that if a single drop of Zaqqum fell into the oceans of this world, it would spoil the lives of everyone on earth. Imagine then the condition of those who must eat it to fill their bellies! (Tirmidhi)"
  },
  67: {
    "Then on top of that they will be given a blend of boiling drink": "After eating from Zaqqum, their throats will burn and they will be desperately thirsty. But the only drink available to them is boiling water (Hameem), mixed with the foul residue of Zaqqum. This scalding drink will tear through their insides, adding pain upon pain. While the people of Paradise drink pure, delicious wine that causes no harm, the people of Hell drink boiling water that destroys them."
  },
  68: {
    "Then they will ultimately return to ˹their place in˺ Hell": "After being forced to eat and drink these punishments, they will be returned to their positions in Hellfire. This cycle of torment continues endlessly. There is no relief, no break, and no escape. They go from one punishment to another, and then back again. This is the eternal fate of those who rejected Allah's guidance and persisted in wrongdoing."
  },
  69: {
    "Indeed, they found their forefathers astray": "Allah explains the root cause of many people's misguidance: they found their ancestors upon a certain path and followed them without thinking. Their forefathers were already lost and astray from the truth, worshipping idols and rejecting prophets. Instead of questioning these practices, the later generations simply accepted them because 'this is what our fathers did.'"
  },
  70: {
    "so they rushed in their footsteps!": "Not only did they follow their ancestors, but they rushed to do so—eagerly and hastily walking the same misguided path. They didn't pause to think, question, or verify. They ran toward misguidance because their fathers were on it. This blind following is extremely dangerous. Islam teaches us to follow evidence and truth, not mere tradition. If our ancestors were right, we follow them. If they were wrong, we must have the courage to choose truth over tradition."
  },
  71: {
    "And surely most of the earlier generations had strayed before them": "Allah informs us that this is not a new problem—most people throughout history have gone astray. The majority is often wrong. Just because many people believe something doesn't make it true. This verse is a warning not to follow the crowd blindly. Truth is not determined by popularity but by evidence and revelation from Allah."
  },
  72: {
    "although We had certainly sent warners among them": "Despite the widespread misguidance, Allah did not leave humanity without guidance. He sent warners—prophets and messengers—to every generation and community. These warners called people to the truth and warned them of the consequences of disbelief. So no one can claim they were not given a chance to know the truth. Allah's justice is complete: He always sends guidance before punishment."
  },
  73: {
    "See then what was the end of those who had been warned": "Allah invites us to look at history and see what happened to those who rejected the warnings. Their civilizations were destroyed, their power crumbled, and they faced punishment in this world before the Hereafter. The ruins of past nations stand as evidence of what happens when people reject Allah's messengers. These historical lessons are meant to make us reflect and avoid their mistakes."
  },
  74: {
    "But not the chosen servants of Allah": "The exception is always the sincere believers—the chosen servants of Allah who accepted the truth and followed the messengers. They were saved from destruction in this world and will be saved from punishment in the Hereafter. Throughout history, while entire nations were destroyed, the believers among them were rescued. This pattern repeats: Noah and his followers were saved, Lot and his family were saved, Moses and his people were saved. Sincerity to Allah is the key to salvation."
  },
  75: {
    "Indeed, Noah cried out to Us, and how excellent are We in responding!": "Prophet Noah called upon Allah after 950 years of preaching to his people with little success. His people mocked him, rejected him, and even threatened him. Finally, he prayed to Allah for help against these persistent disbelievers. And Allah responded—and what an excellent response it was! Allah heard his prayer and answered it completely. This shows that Allah always hears the prayers of His sincere servants, especially those who have been patient through hardship."
  },
  76: {
    "We delivered him and his family from the great distress": "Allah saved Noah and his believing family members from the great calamity—the massive flood that drowned the entire earth. After centuries of suffering abuse and rejection, Noah and those who believed with him were rescued. The 'great distress' refers both to the flood itself and to the long years of hardship Noah endured while calling his people to Allah. Allah's help came at the perfect time."
  },
  77: {
    "and made his descendants the sole survivors": "Allah made Noah's offspring the only survivors of humanity. Every human being alive today is a descendant of Noah. The disbelievers who mocked him left no legacy—their lineage ended with the flood. But Noah's legacy continues through all of humanity. This is a profound honor: the man they ridiculed became the father of all future generations."
  },
  78: {
    "And We blessed him ˹with honourable mention˺ among later generations": "Allah preserved Noah's good reputation for all future generations. His name is mentioned with honor in the Quran, the Bible, and throughout human history. While his enemies are forgotten or remembered only for their wickedness, Noah is remembered as a righteous prophet of Allah. This is part of Allah's reward for His faithful servants—honor that extends beyond their lifetime."
  },
  79: {
    "\"Peace be upon Noah among all peoples.\"": "Allah sends peace and blessings upon Noah—a greeting of honor that echoes throughout all of creation and all of time. When Muslims mention Noah, they say 'peace be upon him.' This divine greeting elevates Noah's status and serves as a model for how the righteous are honored. The one whom his people mocked is now greeted with peace by Allah Himself."
  },
  80: {
    "Indeed, this is how We reward the good-doers": "Allah explains that this honor—salvation, surviving legacy, and eternal good reputation—is how He rewards those who do good (Muhsineen). Those who worship Allah with excellence, remain patient through trials, and fulfill their mission will be rewarded abundantly in this life and the next. The reward of the righteous is not limited to the Hereafter; it includes honor and remembrance in this world as well."
  },
  81: {
    "˹For˺ he was truly one of Our faithful servants": "Allah confirms the reason for Noah's great reward: he was among Allah's believing, faithful servants. His faith was genuine and deep. Despite 950 years of rejection and hardship, he never wavered in his belief or his mission. This verse emphasizes that true faith, demonstrated through patience and perseverance, is what earns Allah's pleasure and reward."
  },
  82: {
    "Then We drowned the others": "After saving Noah and the believers, Allah drowned everyone else—all those who rejected the message despite centuries of warning. This was complete justice. They had been given every opportunity to believe, but they chose to mock and reject. Their end was total destruction, while Noah and his followers began a new chapter of human history. This is a warning for all future generations: rejection of Allah's messengers leads to destruction."
  },
  83: {
    "And indeed, one of those who followed his way was Abraham": "Allah connects the story of Abraham to Noah, showing that Abraham followed the same path of monotheism and submission to Allah. Abraham came generations after Noah but carried the same message: worship Allah alone. This shows the continuity of the prophetic mission—each prophet built upon the foundation of those before him, all calling to the same truth."
  },
  84: {
    "˹Remember˺ when he came to his Lord with a pure heart": "Abraham approached Allah with a 'qalb saleem'—a sound, pure, sincere heart. This heart was free from polytheism, hypocrisy, and attachment to anything other than Allah. Having a pure heart is essential for true faith. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'There is a piece of flesh in the body; if it is sound, the whole body is sound, and if it is corrupt, the whole body is corrupt. Indeed, it is the heart.' (Sahih Bukhari) Abraham's heart was completely devoted to Allah."
  },
  85: {
    "and said to his father and his people, \"What are you worshipping?\"": "Abraham directly confronted his father Azar and his community about their worship. He asked them a simple but profound question: What exactly are you worshipping? This question was designed to make them think. They worshipped idols without ever questioning why. Abraham's approach was to engage their minds, not just preach at them. He wanted them to reflect on the absurdity of their practices."
  },
  86: {
    "Is it false gods that you desire instead of Allah?": "Abraham continued his questioning: Do you really want these false, fabricated gods instead of the true God—Allah? He exposed the falsehood of their idols. These 'gods' were lies, inventions with no reality or power. Abraham challenged them to consider why they would choose powerless fabrications over the all-powerful Creator."
  },
  87: {
    "What then do you expect from the Lord of all worlds?\"": "Abraham asked them a sobering question: What do you think the Lord of all creation will do to you for this? Do you expect Him to overlook your worship of false gods? Do you think there will be no consequence for rejecting Him? This question was meant to instill awareness of accountability. They couldn't ignore the Lord of the universe forever."
  },
  88: {
    "He later looked up to the stars ˹in contemplation˺": "On one occasion, when his people were preparing for a festival to worship their idols, Abraham looked up at the stars. His people practiced astrology and believed the stars influenced events. Abraham used this to his advantage, appearing to consult the stars as they did."
  },
  89: {
    "then said, \"I am really sick.\"": "Abraham announced that he was feeling sick and could not join them for their festival. This was a strategic statement—he wanted to stay behind while everyone else left to attend their celebrations. Some scholars say he was 'sick' of their idol worship, meaning it disgusted him spiritually. Either way, this gave him the opportunity he needed to confront the idols directly."
  },
  90: {
    "So they turned their backs on him and went away": "His people believed him and left him behind, heading to their festival. They had no idea what Abraham was planning. This shows how Allah facilitated Abraham's mission—He arranged circumstances so Abraham could carry out his plan to expose the falsehood of the idols."
  },
  91: {
    "Then he ˹stealthily˺ advanced towards their gods, and said ˹mockingly˺, \"Will you not eat ˹your offerings˺?\"": "Once alone, Abraham approached the idols. Food offerings had been placed before them as part of the worship rituals. Abraham mocked the idols by asking them: Why don't you eat? The food is right in front of you! Of course, the idols couldn't eat—they were just stone and wood. This was Abraham's way of highlighting their powerlessness."
  },
  92: {
    "What is wrong with you that you cannot speak?\"": "Abraham continued his mockery: What's wrong with you? Why can't you speak? He addressed them as if they were living beings, exposing how absurd it was to worship things that couldn't even respond. If these idols couldn't eat, speak, or move, how could they help anyone? How could they be worthy of worship?"
  },
  93: {
    "Then he swiftly turned on them, striking ˹them˺ with his right hand": "After making his point, Abraham took action. He struck the idols with his right hand (symbolizing strength and power), breaking them into pieces. He destroyed all of them except the largest one—a strategic decision that would serve his argument later. This bold action demonstrated his complete rejection of idolatry and his courage in standing for truth."
  },
  94: {
    "Later, his people came rushing towards him ˹furiously˺": "When the people returned and found their gods destroyed, they were furious. They quickly figured out that Abraham was responsible—he was the only one who hadn't attended the festival and was known for criticizing the idols. They rushed toward him in anger, ready to confront and punish him."
  },
  95: {
    "He argued, \"How can you worship what you carve ˹with your own hands˺\"": "Instead of being intimidated, Abraham used this moment to drive home his message. He asked them: How can you worship things that you yourselves carve? You take a piece of stone or wood, shape it with your own hands, and then bow down to it? The creator should be worshipped, not the creation—and certainly not something created by the worshipper himself! This logical argument exposed the absurdity of idol worship."
  },
  96: {
    "when it is Allah Who created you and whatever you do?\"": "Abraham completed his argument: Allah is the One who created you—your hands, your skills, and even the materials you use to carve idols. Everything you have and everything you do comes from Allah. So why worship your own creations when you should worship the One who created you? This powerful reasoning left them without a valid response."
  },
  97: {
    "They said ˹to one another˺, \"Build him a furnace and cast him into the blazing fire.\"": "Unable to defeat Abraham's arguments, his people resorted to violence. They decided to build a massive fire and throw him into it. When people cannot counter truth with reason, they often turn to force. This is the way of tyrants throughout history. But Abraham was not afraid—he trusted in Allah completely."
  },
  98: {
    "And so they sought to harm him, but We made them inferior": "They plotted against Abraham, intending to destroy him. But Allah had other plans. Allah commanded the fire to be cool and safe for Abraham, and he emerged unharmed. Their plot completely failed. Those who tried to bring Abraham down were themselves brought low and humiliated. Allah made them the inferior ones—their plan backfired, and Abraham's status was elevated even higher. This is a powerful lesson: those who oppose Allah's chosen servants will never succeed. Allah protects His own."
  },
  99: {
    "He later said, \"I am leaving ˹in obedience˺ to my Lord. He will guide me.\"": "After surviving the fire and realizing his people would never accept the truth, Abraham decided to migrate. He declared that he was leaving for the sake of Allah—moving to a land where he could worship Allah freely and continue his mission. His trust in Allah was absolute: 'He will guide me.' Abraham didn't know exactly where he was going, but he knew that Allah would show him the way. This is the essence of Tawakkul (reliance on Allah)—taking action while trusting Allah for the outcome. Abraham's migration (Hijrah) set a precedent for all believers who must sometimes leave their homes for the sake of their faith."
  },
  100: {
    "My Lord! Bless me with righteous offspring.\"": "As Abraham embarked on his new journey, he made a beautiful supplication to Allah, asking for righteous children. He didn't just ask for children—he specifically asked for righteous ones. This shows his priorities: he valued quality of character over mere quantity. He wanted children who would continue the message of monotheism after him. This dua teaches us to pray for righteous offspring, not just successful ones by worldly standards. The Prophet ﷺ taught us that one of the things that benefits a person after death is 'a righteous child who prays for them.' (Sahih Muslim)"
  },
  101: {
    "So We gave him good news of a forbearing son": "Allah answered Abraham's prayer with wonderful news: he would have a son who would be 'haleem'—forbearing, patient, and gentle. This son was Ismail (Ishmael), the firstborn of Abraham through Hajar (Hagar). The description 'forbearing' foreshadows the incredible patience Ismail would show later when faced with a tremendous test. Allah not only granted Abraham's request but gave him a son with an exceptional character. This shows that when we make sincere duas, Allah may give us even more than we asked for."
  },
  102: {
    "Then when the boy reached the age to work with him": "Ismail grew up until he reached an age where he could walk, work, and assist his father. This was probably around the age of thirteen—old enough to understand and participate in life's activities. Father and son had developed a close bond, making what was about to happen even more significant.",
    "Abraham said, \"O my dear son! I have seen in a dream that I ˹must˺ sacrifice you. So tell me what you think.\"": "Abraham received a command from Allah through a dream—and the dreams of prophets are revelation. He was commanded to sacrifice his beloved son, the child he had prayed for and waited so long to have. Instead of hiding this from Ismail, Abraham shared it with him, addressing him with love: 'O my dear son.' He asked for Ismail's thoughts, not because he would disobey Allah if Ismail disagreed, but to prepare his son and involve him in this act of worship. This shows Abraham's respect for his son and his approach of consultation even in the most difficult situations.",
    "He replied, \"O my dear father! Do as you are commanded. Allah willing, you will find me steadfast.\"": "Ismail's response was extraordinary. This young boy, upon hearing that his own father must sacrifice him by Allah's command, did not panic, cry, or run away. Instead, he responded with complete submission: 'Do as you are commanded.' He encouraged his father to obey Allah and promised to be patient. He added 'Allah willing' (In sha Allah), showing humility—he didn't boast about his own strength but relied on Allah to grant him patience. This response demonstrates why Allah described him as 'forbearing.' Both father and son showed the highest level of faith and submission."
  },
  103: {
    "Then when they submitted ˹to Allah's Will˺": "The key word here is 'aslama'—they submitted. Both Abraham and Ismail completely surrendered to Allah's command. This is the essence of Islam: submission to Allah's will, even when it's difficult or beyond our understanding. They didn't question, complain, or delay. They accepted and acted.",
    "and Abraham laid him on the side of his forehead ˹for sacrifice˺": "Abraham laid Ismail face down, so he wouldn't have to look at his son's face while carrying out the sacrifice. This detail shows the human emotion involved—Abraham loved his son deeply, and this was incredibly painful for him. Yet his love for Allah was greater. He positioned Ismail and prepared to fulfill the command. This moment represents the peak of faith and sacrifice in human history."
  },
  104: {
    "We called out to him, \"O Abraham!\"": "At the critical moment, just as Abraham was about to complete the sacrifice, Allah called out to him. The test was complete. Allah never intended for Ismail to actually be killed—He wanted to test the sincerity and obedience of both father and son. And they passed with the highest marks. Allah's call came as a relief and a confirmation of their faith."
  },
  105: {
    "You have already fulfilled the vision.\"": "Allah told Abraham that he had already fulfilled the dream. The purpose of the command was to test his willingness to obey, not to actually take his son's life. Abraham proved his complete devotion to Allah by being willing to sacrifice what was most precious to him. His intention and action were accepted as if the sacrifice had been completed.",
    "Indeed, this is how We reward the good-doers": "Allah explains that this miraculous intervention—saving Ismail at the last moment and accepting their willingness as complete obedience—is how He rewards the Muhsineen (those who do good with excellence). When a person gives their all for Allah, Allah never lets them down. He rewards their sincerity in ways beyond imagination."
  },
  106: {
    "That was truly a revealing test": "Allah confirms that this was a clear, manifest trial—one of the greatest tests any human being has ever faced. Being asked to sacrifice your own child with your own hands is unimaginably difficult. This test revealed the true depths of Abraham and Ismail's faith. It separated genuine devotion from mere words. True faith is proven through trials, and this was the ultimate trial."
  },
  107: {
    "And We ransomed his son with a great sacrifice": "Allah replaced Ismail with a ram (or sheep) to be sacrificed instead. This animal was sent from Paradise and was described as 'great' because of its significance and origin. This event is commemorated every year during Eid al-Adha (the Festival of Sacrifice), when Muslims around the world sacrifice animals and distribute the meat to family, friends, and the poor. This practice keeps alive the memory of Abraham's devotion and teaches every generation about sacrifice for Allah's sake."
  },
  108: {
    "and blessed Abraham ˹with honourable mention˺ among later generations": "Just as with Noah, Allah preserved Abraham's good name and reputation for all future generations. Abraham is honored by Muslims, Christians, and Jews alike. He is called 'Khalilullah'—the close friend of Allah. His legacy of monotheism and sacrifice continues to inspire billions of people. Every prayer by Muslims includes blessings upon Abraham and his family."
  },
  109: {
    "\"Peace be upon Abraham.\"": "Allah Himself sends peace upon Abraham—the highest honor possible. This divine greeting affirms Abraham's exalted status and serves as an example for all believers. When we mention Abraham, we say 'peace be upon him,' following Allah's own practice. This greeting of peace will echo until the Day of Judgment."
  },
  110: {
    "This is how We reward the good-doers": "Allah repeats that this is His way of rewarding those who excel in their worship and obedience. The pattern is consistent: sincerity leads to salvation, honor, and eternal reward. Those who sacrifice for Allah's sake are never losers—they gain far more than they give up."
  },
  111: {
    "He was truly one of Our faithful servants": "Allah again confirms that Abraham was among His believing servants. This title—'servant of Allah'—is the highest honor. Abraham's faith was proven through the most difficult test, and he emerged victorious. His servitude to Allah was complete and sincere."
  },
  112: {
    "We ˹later˺ gave him good news of Isaac—a prophet, and one of the righteous": "After the great trial and Abraham's proven devotion, Allah gave him more good news: another son, Isaac (Ishaq), who would also be a prophet and a righteous person. This was an additional blessing, showing that Allah's rewards continue to multiply for the faithful. Abraham's prayer for righteous offspring was answered abundantly—both Ismail and Isaac became prophets, and from their descendants came many more prophets, including Muhammad ﷺ (from Ismail's line) and Moses and Jesus (from Isaac's line)."
  },
  113: {
    "We blessed him and Isaac as well": "Allah blessed both Abraham and Isaac with countless blessings—prophethood, righteous descendants, good reputation, and much more. Allah's blessings extended through their lineage for generations.",
    "Some of their descendants did good, while others clearly wronged themselves": "However, Allah clarifies an important point: being descended from a righteous person does not guarantee righteousness. Some of Abraham and Isaac's descendants were good and righteous, while others were wrongdoers who harmed themselves through sin and disbelief. Each person is responsible for their own choices. Lineage alone cannot save anyone—what matters is personal faith and action. This is a lesson for all: we cannot rely on the piety of our ancestors; we must build our own relationship with Allah."
  },
  114: {
    "And We certainly showed favour to Moses and Aaron": "Allah mentions another set of honored prophets: Moses (Musa) and his brother Aaron (Harun). Allah bestowed special favors upon them—prophethood, miracles, victory over Pharaoh, and the privilege of leading the Children of Israel. These two brothers worked together in their prophetic mission, with Moses as the primary messenger and Aaron as his helper and spokesman."
  },
  115: {
    "and delivered them and their people from the great distress": "Allah saved Moses, Aaron, and the Children of Israel from the 'great distress'—the oppression, slavery, and persecution they suffered under Pharaoh in Egypt. For generations, they were enslaved, their baby boys were killed, and they were treated as inferior. Allah heard their cries and sent Moses to deliver them. This deliverance is one of the greatest examples of Allah rescuing the oppressed."
  },
  116: {
    "We helped them so it was they who prevailed": "Allah supported Moses and the believers against the most powerful ruler of that time—Pharaoh. Despite Pharaoh's massive army and resources, Allah made the oppressed believers victorious. The sea split for them, they crossed safely, and Pharaoh and his army were drowned. The ones who had been weak and enslaved became the victors. This shows that true victory comes from Allah, not from military strength or numbers."
  },
  117: {
    "We gave them the clear Scripture": "Allah gave Moses and Aaron the Torah—a clear book of guidance with laws, teachings, and wisdom. This scripture was 'mustabeen'—clear and manifest, leaving no confusion about right and wrong. Divine scriptures are a tremendous blessing, providing a roadmap for life. The Torah guided the Children of Israel for generations until it was eventually altered by human hands."
  },
  118: {
    "and guided them to the Straight Path": "Beyond giving them scripture, Allah guided Moses and Aaron to the Straight Path—the path of true faith, correct worship, and righteous living. This guidance is the greatest blessing of all. Without it, even possessing scripture would not be enough. Allah guided their hearts to understand, believe, and practice the truth."
  },
  119: {
    "And We blessed them ˹with honourable mention˺ among later generations": "Like Noah and Abraham before them, Moses and Aaron were granted lasting honor and good reputation. They are remembered and respected by billions of people across different faiths. Their story is told in the Quran, the Bible, and countless other sources. Allah preserved their legacy as an inspiration for all generations."
  },
  120: {
    "\"Peace be upon Moses and Aaron.\"": "Allah sends His peace upon both Moses and Aaron, honoring them with this divine greeting. This peace from the Lord of all worlds is the ultimate recognition of their service and sacrifice. Muslims honor them whenever their names are mentioned by saying 'peace be upon them.'"
  },
  121: {
    "Indeed, this is how We reward the good-doers": "Once again, Allah affirms His consistent practice of rewarding those who excel in faith and good deeds. The pattern is clear: prophets who remained faithful, faced trials with patience, and delivered Allah's message are rewarded with victory in this life, eternal honor, and the ultimate success in the Hereafter. This same reward awaits anyone who follows their path."
  },
  122: {
    "They were truly ˹two˺ of Our faithful servants": "Allah concludes the account of Moses and Aaron by affirming that they were among His believing servants. Despite facing one of history's greatest tyrants, despite the ingratitude of some of their own people, despite years of hardship—they remained faithful to Allah. Their servitude was genuine and complete, and Allah honored them for it. This description—'faithful servants'—is the title every believer should aspire to earn."
  },
  123: {
    "And Elias was indeed one of the messengers": "Allah introduces another prophet: Elias (known as Elijah in the Bible). He was sent to the people of Baalbek in the region of modern-day Lebanon and Syria. Like all messengers, he came with the same core message: worship Allah alone. Allah confirms his status as a true messenger, part of the blessed chain of prophets sent throughout history to guide humanity."
  },
  124: {
    "˹Remember˺ when he said to his people, \"Will you not fear ˹Allah˺?\"": "Elias called out to his people with a fundamental question: Will you not have Taqwa (fear and consciousness of Allah)? This question aimed to awaken their hearts and make them think about their accountability before Allah. Taqwa is the foundation of righteousness—it means being aware that Allah sees everything and will hold us accountable, which should motivate us to obey Him and avoid disobedience."
  },
  125: {
    "Do you call upon ˹the idol of˺ Ba'l and abandon the Best of Creators—": "Elias confronted his people about their idol worship. 'Ba'l' was a famous idol worshipped in that region—the name means 'lord' or 'master,' and it was considered a god of rain and fertility. Elias asked them incredulously: How can you worship this lifeless idol and abandon Allah, who is the Best of Creators? This comparison highlighted the absurdity of their choice. They were leaving the perfect Creator for a powerless creation."
  },
  126: {
    "Allah, your Lord and the Lord of your forefathers?\"": "Elias reminded them that Allah is not just some distant deity—He is their Lord, their Creator, their Sustainer, and He was also the Lord of all their ancestors. Their forefathers who were righteous worshipped Allah alone. By worshipping Ba'l, they were betraying the true faith of their earliest ancestors who followed the prophets. This argument appeals to both reason and heritage."
  },
  127: {
    "But they rejected him, so they will certainly be brought ˹for punishment˺": "Despite Elias's clear message and logical arguments, his people rejected him. They chose to continue worshipping their idol rather than accept the truth. Allah warns that because of this rejection, they will certainly be brought for punishment on the Day of Judgment. No one who rejects Allah's messengers will escape accountability. Their stubbornness sealed their fate."
  },
  128: {
    "But not the chosen servants of Allah": "As always, there is an exception: the sincere, chosen servants of Allah among Elias's people will be saved. Those who accepted his message and worshipped Allah alone will not share in the punishment of the rejectors. This consistent theme throughout the Surah emphasizes that sincerity to Allah is the key to salvation, regardless of what the majority around you choose to do."
  },
  129: {
    "We blessed him ˹with honourable mention˺ among later generations": "Allah preserved Elias's good name and reputation for all future generations. Though his people rejected him, history has honored him. He is remembered in the Quran, respected in Islamic tradition, and his story continues to inspire. While his opponents are forgotten or remembered only for their wickedness, Elias lives on in honorable memory."
  },
  130: {
    "\"Peace be upon Elias.\"": "Allah sends His peace and blessings upon Elias. This divine greeting is the highest honor, confirming his status among the righteous prophets. The greeting of peace from Allah echoes throughout time, and believers continue this practice by saying 'peace be upon him' when mentioning any prophet."
  },
  131: {
    "Indeed, this is how We reward the good-doers": "Allah reaffirms His way of rewarding those who excel in worship and righteousness. The Muhsineen—those who do good with excellence and sincerity—receive honor, protection, and eternal reward. This promise applies to every believer who strives to follow the path of the prophets."
  },
  132: {
    "He was truly one of Our faithful servants": "Allah concludes Elias's story by confirming that he was among the faithful servants. His faith was genuine, tested, and proven. He stood firm against idol worship despite opposition, and Allah honored him for it. This title is the ultimate recognition of a life lived in devotion to Allah."
  },
  133: {
    "And Lot was indeed one of the messengers": "Allah introduces Prophet Lot (Lut), the nephew of Prophet Abraham. Lot was sent to the people of Sodom and Gomorrah, cities known for their extreme wickedness and immorality. He called them to worship Allah and abandon their sinful practices, particularly the sin of homosexuality, which they practiced openly and shamelessly."
  },
  134: {
    "˹Remember˺ when We delivered him and all of his family": "Allah saved Lot and his entire believing family from the destruction that befell his people. When Allah's punishment came upon the wicked cities, Lot and his followers were commanded to leave at night and not look back. This deliverance shows Allah's mercy toward the righteous—He always provides a way out for those who believe and obey."
  },
  135: {
    "except an old woman, who was one of the doomed": "There was one exception from Lot's household: his wife. She was an old woman who did not truly believe in Lot's message. Though she lived with a prophet, her heart was with the disbelievers. She was among those destined for destruction. When the punishment came, she looked back (disobeying the command) and was caught in the destruction. This teaches us that family ties to a righteous person cannot save someone who chooses disbelief. Each person is responsible for their own faith."
  },
  136: {
    "Then We ˹utterly˺ destroyed the rest": "After saving Lot and the believers, Allah completely destroyed the remaining people of those cities. The destruction was total and devastating—the cities were overturned, and stones of baked clay rained down upon them. Nothing was left of their civilization except ruins. This punishment matched the severity and openness of their sins."
  },
  137: {
    "You ˹Meccans˺ certainly pass by their ruins day": "Allah addresses the people of Makkah directly, pointing out that they regularly travel past the ruins of Lot's people during their trade journeys to Syria. In the morning light, they can see the remnants of those destroyed cities near the Dead Sea. These ruins are physical evidence of Allah's punishment—not ancient myths, but real places they themselves witness."
  },
  138: {
    "and night. Will you not then understand?": "They pass by these ruins both in the morning and at night during their journeys. Allah asks: Will you not use your intellect? Will you not reflect on what happened to these people and why? The ruins are a warning sign, yet the Makkans ignored them. This verse challenges us all: when we see signs of Allah's power and punishment, do we reflect and take heed, or do we carelessly pass by?"
  },
  139: {
    "And Jonah was indeed one of the messengers": "Allah introduces Prophet Jonah (Yunus), known in the Quran as the 'companion of the whale.' He was sent to the people of Nineveh in ancient Iraq. Jonah's story is unique among the prophets because it includes a moment of human weakness followed by sincere repentance and Allah's overwhelming mercy."
  },
  140: {
    "˹Remember˺ when he fled to the overloaded ship": "After warning his people and seeing their continued rejection, Jonah became frustrated and left before Allah had permitted him to do so. He boarded a ship that was already heavily loaded with passengers and cargo. The word 'fled' (abaqa) indicates that he left in a manner like a servant running away from his master—he departed without Allah's permission. This was a mistake that Jonah would deeply regret."
  },
  141: {
    "Then ˹to save it from sinking,˺ he drew straws ˹with other passengers˺. He lost ˹and was thrown overboard˺": "During the voyage, a violent storm threatened to sink the overloaded ship. The sailors believed someone aboard had brought bad fortune, so they drew lots to determine who should be thrown overboard to lighten the load and appease the sea. Jonah's name came up—perhaps Allah arranged this as part of His plan. Jonah was cast into the raging sea, a consequence that began a powerful lesson in humility and reliance on Allah."
  },
  142: {
    "Then the whale engulfed him while he was blameworthy": "A huge whale (or large fish) swallowed Jonah whole. He was taken into the belly of this creature while being 'muleem'—blameworthy or deserving of blame. Jonah himself acknowledged that he had made a mistake by leaving his post without permission. He was not sinless in this situation; he recognized his error. This detail makes Jonah's story profoundly relatable—even prophets can make mistakes, and what matters is how they respond."
  },
  143: {
    "Had he not ˹constantly˺ glorified ˹Allah˺": "In the darkness of the whale's belly—darkness upon darkness, deep in the sea—Jonah turned to Allah in sincere repentance. He glorified Allah and acknowledged his wrongdoing with the famous supplication: 'There is no god except You; glory be to You. Indeed, I have been among the wrongdoers.' (Quran 21:87) This constant remembrance and glorification of Allah was his lifeline. His history of being among those who regularly glorified Allah saved him."
  },
  144: {
    "he would have certainly remained in its belly until the Day of Resurrection": "Allah reveals that if Jonah had not been someone who glorified Allah and repented sincerely, he would have remained in the whale's belly until the Day of Resurrection. The whale would have become his grave. This dramatic statement shows how serious his situation was and how crucial his repentance was to his rescue. It also demonstrates the immense power of dhikr (remembrance of Allah) and istighfar (seeking forgiveness)."
  },
  145: {
    "But We cast him onto the open ˹shore˺, ˹totally˺ worn out": "Allah commanded the whale to release Jonah, and he was cast onto a barren shore. He emerged in a weakened, sickly state—his body affected by the ordeal of being inside the whale. He was physically exhausted and ill, but he was alive. Allah had accepted his repentance and rescued him from an impossible situation. This moment of emergence represents rebirth and a second chance."
  },
  146: {
    "and caused a squash plant to grow over him": "To help Jonah recover, Allah caused a gourd or squash plant (yaqteen) to grow over him. This plant provided shade from the sun, its leaves were soft and soothing, and its fruit provided nourishment. Some scholars mention that flies wouldn't come near this plant, allowing Jonah to rest peacefully. Every detail of his recovery was arranged by Allah's mercy. From the depths of the ocean to the care of a simple plant, Allah's providence was complete."
  },
  147: {
    "We ˹later˺ sent him ˹back˺ to ˹his city of˺ at least one hundred thousand people": "After Jonah recovered, Allah sent him back to complete his mission. He returned to his people in Nineveh—a city of one hundred thousand people or more. This time, Jonah went with renewed commitment and humility. His trial had transformed him. He was no longer the frustrated prophet who had fled; he was now a seasoned servant of Allah who had experienced divine mercy firsthand."
  },
  148: {
    "who then believed ˹in him˺, so We allowed them enjoyment for a while": "Remarkably, when Jonah returned and delivered his message, all one hundred thousand people believed! This is one of the few examples in prophetic history where an entire nation accepted the truth. When they saw the signs of impending punishment, they repented sincerely, and Allah lifted the punishment from them. They were granted enjoyment of life 'for a while'—meaning until their natural deaths. This story shows that sincere repentance can avert even certain punishment. The people of Jonah are proof that it is never too late to turn back to Allah."
  },
  149: {
    "Ask them ˹O Prophet˺ if your Lord has daughters, while the pagans ˹prefer to˺ have sons": "Allah commands the Prophet ﷺ to question the pagan Arabs about their contradictory beliefs. They claimed that the angels were Allah's daughters, yet in their own culture, they despised having daughters and preferred sons. Some even buried their baby girls alive out of shame. So how could they attribute to Allah what they considered inferior for themselves? This exposes the absurdity and inconsistency of their beliefs—they assigned to Allah what they would never accept for themselves."
  },
  150: {
    "Or ˹ask them˺ if We created the angels as females right before their eyes": "Allah challenges them further: Were they present when the angels were created? Did they witness the angels being created as females? Of course not. They had no knowledge whatsoever about the nature of angels, yet they made definitive claims about them. This verse exposes how they spoke about the unseen without any evidence or revelation—purely from their own imagination and fabrication."
  },
  151: {
    "Indeed, it is one of their ˹outrageous˺ fabrications to say": "Allah declares that what they say is pure fabrication—lies invented from their own minds. The word 'ifk' means a lie that is completely overturned from the truth, the worst kind of falsehood. Their claims about Allah and the angels had no basis in reality, revelation, or reason. They simply made things up and presented them as religious truth."
  },
  152: {
    "\"Allah has children.\" They are simply liars": "Their specific claim—that Allah has children—is identified as a blatant lie. Allah does not have children. He is not like His creation. He does not need offspring for continuation or support. The concept of Allah having children is completely incompatible with His nature as the Eternal, Self-Sufficient Creator. Those who make such claims are confirmed as liars."
  },
  153: {
    "Has He chosen daughters over sons?": "Allah asks rhetorically: If Allah were to have children (which He does not), would He choose daughters—the very thing you consider inferior and shameful—over sons, whom you prefer? By their own flawed logic, this makes no sense. This argument uses their own cultural biases to expose the contradiction in their claims. Of course, the correct understanding is that Allah has no children at all."
  },
  154: {
    "What is the matter with you? How do you judge?": "Allah expresses amazement at their flawed reasoning. What is wrong with you? How do you make such judgments? Their claims were not based on any sound logic or evidence. This verse challenges them—and all people—to examine the basis of their beliefs. Are your beliefs founded on revelation and reason, or on inherited falsehoods and personal desires?"
  },
  155: {
    "Will you not then be mindful?": "Allah calls them to reflection and remembrance. Will you not think? Will you not use the minds Allah gave you to recognize the truth? The faculty of reason is a gift from Allah, and it should lead people to recognize His Oneness and reject false beliefs. Heedlessness is the enemy of faith."
  },
  156: {
    "Or do you have ˹any˺ compelling proof?": "Allah challenges them to produce evidence for their claims. Do you have any clear authority—any revelation from Allah or logical proof—that supports what you say? The answer is no. They had nothing but assumptions and inherited traditions. In Islam, beliefs must be based on evidence, not wishful thinking or cultural practices."
  },
  157: {
    "Then bring ˹us˺ your scripture, if what you say is true!": "Allah demands that they produce their evidence—a scripture, a divine book that supports their claims. If they are truthful, let them show their proof. Of course, they had no such scripture because their beliefs were fabricated. This challenge silences them and proves that their claims have no divine backing."
  },
  158: {
    "They have also established a ˹marital˺ relationship between Him and the jinn": "The pagans went even further in their fabrications, claiming that Allah had a relationship with the jinn—some even claiming the angels were offspring of such a union. This is an absurd and offensive claim that degrades Allah's majesty.",
    "Yet the jinn ˹themselves˺ know well that such people will certainly be brought ˹for punishment˺": "Ironically, the jinn themselves know that these claims are false and that those who make them will be brought for punishment. Even the jinn recognize Allah's transcendence above such ridiculous claims. The very beings they associate with Allah will testify against them."
  },
  159: {
    "Glorified is Allah far above what they claim!": "Allah declares His absolute purity and transcendence above all the false things they attribute to Him. 'Subhan Allah' means Allah is free from all imperfections, deficiencies, and false descriptions. He has no children, no partners, no weaknesses. He is perfect in every way, and all their claims are nothing but lies."
  },
  160: {
    "But not the chosen servants of Allah": "The sincere servants of Allah do not make such false claims. They worship Allah as He deserves to be worshipped, recognizing His Oneness and transcendence. They are protected from these fabrications because they follow revelation, not cultural myths or personal desires. Once again, the exception of the sincere believers is highlighted."
  },
  161: {
    "Surely you ˹pagans˺ and whatever ˹idols˺ you worship": "Allah addresses the pagans and their idols together, grouping them as one party. They are united in falsehood, but their unity gives them no power. Allah is about to expose how utterly helpless they all are."
  },
  162: {
    "can never lure ˹anyone˺ away from Him": "Neither the pagans nor their idols have the power to lead anyone astray from Allah except by His permission. They cannot tempt anyone away from Allah's path if Allah has decreed guidance for that person. Misguidance only occurs for those whom Allah has already decreed will go astray based on their own choices. The idols have no power whatsoever—they cannot guide or misguide anyone."
  },
  163: {
    "except those ˹destined˺ to burn in Hell": "The only ones who are led astray by idols and false deities are those who have already chosen misguidance and are destined for Hell because of their own rejection of truth. Allah allows them to be deceived because they themselves chose deception over guidance. Those whom Allah protects cannot be swayed by any false deity or misguided person."
  },
  164: {
    "˹The angels respond,˺ \"There is not one of us without an assigned station ˹of worship˺\"": "The angels themselves speak, distancing themselves from the false claims made about them. They declare that each angel has a specific rank and position assigned by Allah. They are servants with duties, not deities or children of Allah. They worship Allah in their designated places with complete obedience and devotion."
  },
  165: {
    "We are indeed the ones lined up in ranks ˹for Allah˺": "The angels affirm that they are the ones who stand in rows before Allah—worshipping, glorifying, and obeying Him. This connects back to the opening verses of the Surah where Allah swore by the angels lined up in ranks. The angels clarify their true role: they are worshippers, not objects of worship."
  },
  166: {
    "And we are indeed the ones ˹constantly˺ glorifying ˹His praise˺": "The angels declare that they continuously glorify Allah (Tasbeeh). Day and night, without fatigue or interruption, they declare Allah's perfection. They do not have the characteristics pagans attributed to them—they are humble servants devoted entirely to worshipping Allah. Their testimony refutes all false claims about them."
  },
  167: {
    "They certainly used to say": "Allah exposes the hypocrisy of the Makkan pagans by recalling what they used to say before the Quran was revealed. They had made claims about what they would do if only they received revelation like previous nations."
  },
  168: {
    "\"If only we had a Reminder like ˹those of˺ earlier peoples\"": "Before the Quran came, the pagans would say: If only we had a scripture like the Jews and Christians have! If only we had a reminder from Allah like previous nations received! They claimed that they would be better than those nations if given the same opportunity."
  },
  169: {
    "we would have truly been Allah's devoted servants.\"": "They boasted that if given revelation, they would have become sincere, devoted servants of Allah. They criticized the Jews and Christians for not properly following their scriptures and claimed they would be different. These were bold claims made when they had no scripture to test their sincerity."
  },
  170: {
    "But ˹now˺ they reject it, so they will soon know": "When the Quran came—the very Reminder they claimed to want—they rejected it! Their previous claims were exposed as empty words. They never truly wanted guidance; they just wanted to criticize others. Now that the test came, they failed it. Allah warns that they will soon know the consequences of their rejection. This verse is a powerful warning against making religious claims that we don't intend to follow through on."
  },
  171: {
    "Our Word has already gone forth to Our servants, the messengers": "Allah reassures the Prophet ﷺ with a powerful promise. Allah's decree has already been established regarding His messengers—a decree made long before this moment. This promise is certain and unchangeable."
  },
  172: {
    "that they would surely be helped": "The promise is that Allah's messengers will definitely be helped and supported. No matter how strong the opposition seems, no matter how many enemies arise, Allah's help will come. The Prophet ﷺ, facing rejection and persecution in Makkah, is being told that his victory is guaranteed by Allah's eternal decree."
  },
  173: {
    "and that Our forces will certainly prevail": "Allah's forces—the believers, the angels, and all who support His cause—will always be victorious in the end. This doesn't mean believers won't face hardship, but ultimate victory belongs to them. History has proven this promise true: Islam spread despite all opposition, and the Prophet ﷺ achieved complete victory within his lifetime."
  },
  174: {
    "So turn away from the deniers for a while ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah instructs the Prophet ﷺ to turn away from the disbelievers temporarily. This is not a command to give up the mission, but to not let their rejection distress him. He should continue his work while being patient with their mockery. 'For a while' indicates that a time will come when the situation will change—either through their acceptance, their punishment, or the believers' victory."
  },
  175: {
    "You will see ˹what will happen to˺ them, and they too will see!": "The Prophet ﷺ is told that he will witness what befalls the disbelievers—whether punishment in this world or humiliation. And they too will see—they will witness the truth they denied. This verse carries both a promise to the Prophet ﷺ and a warning to the disbelievers. Time will reveal the truth to everyone."
  },
  176: {
    "Do they ˹really˺ wish to hasten Our punishment?": "The disbelievers mockingly asked for Allah's punishment to come quickly, thinking it would never happen. Allah asks: Do they really want to rush the punishment? Are they truly eager for destruction? This rhetorical question highlights their foolishness—they mock what will ultimately destroy them."
  },
  177: {
    "Yet when it descends upon them: how evil will that morning be for those who had been warned!": "When the punishment finally arrives at their doorstep, what a terrible morning it will be for them! The image of punishment descending in the morning suggests a sudden, unexpected calamity—like an army attacking at dawn when people are unprepared. They were warned repeatedly, but they ignored every warning. Their morning of reckoning will be the worst they could imagine."
  },
  178: {
    "And turn away from them for a while": "Allah repeats the instruction to the Prophet ﷺ to turn away from the disbelievers for a period. This repetition emphasizes the message: be patient, don't be affected by their rejection, and trust in Allah's timing. The Prophet's duty is to deliver the message; Allah will handle the rest."
  },
  179: {
    "You will see, and they too will see!": "Again Allah affirms: You will see the outcome, and they will see it too. The Prophet ﷺ saw the victory of Islam in his lifetime—the conquest of Makkah, the spread of Islam throughout Arabia, and the humiliation of those who opposed him. The disbelievers also saw the truth of what they had denied, both in this world and in the Hereafter."
  },
  180: {
    "Glorified is your Lord—the Lord of Honour and Power—above what they claim!": "The Surah concludes with a powerful declaration of Allah's perfection. 'Subhana Rabbika'—Glorified is your Lord! He is the Lord of Honor and Might (Rabb al-'Izzah)—all power, dignity, and glory belong to Him. He is far above and completely free from all the false things the disbelievers attribute to Him. No matter what lies they invent, Allah remains perfect, transcendent, and supreme."
  },
  181: {
    "Peace be upon the messengers": "After glorifying Allah, peace is sent upon all the messengers. Every prophet mentioned in this Surah—Noah, Abraham, Moses, Aaron, Elias, Lot, Jonah—and all other messengers are honored with this greeting of peace. They fulfilled their missions despite opposition, and Allah honors them collectively. This verse teaches us to respect and send peace upon all of Allah's messengers."
  },
  182: {
    "And praise be to Allah—Lord of all worlds": "The Surah ends exactly as Surah Al-Fatiha ends: with praise to Allah, the Lord of all worlds. All praise, thanks, and gratitude belong to Allah—the Creator, Sustainer, and Master of everything that exists. This phrase encapsulates the entire message of the Surah: Allah alone deserves worship and praise, His messengers are honored, and the sincere believers will be rewarded. Everything begins with Allah and returns to Allah. This is the perfect conclusion to a Surah that began with oaths by the angels and ends with the glorification of their Lord. Al-Hamdulillahi Rabbil 'Alameen."
  }
};